window.MODULES=window.MODULES||{};window.MODULES["adult-congenital"]={"slug": "adult-congenital", "title": "Adult Congenital Heart Disease", "tagline": "A fellowship-level tour of shunts, Eisenmenger physiology, repaired tetralogy, transposition, coarctation, Ebstein, the Fontan, and the systemic right ventricle, with the numeric thresholds and decision points that govern management.", "level": 3, "readMin": 42, "takeaways": ["Shunt closure hinges on hemodynamic significance and reversibility: chamber enlargement and a Qp:Qs above roughly 1.5:1 support closure, but a pulmonary vascular resistance that is fixed and elevated (Eisenmenger physiology) contraindicates it.", "Repaired tetralogy of Fallot is dominated by chronic pulmonary regurgitation; the modern decision is when to intervene on the pulmonary valve before RV dilation becomes irreversible, guided by indexed RV volumes on CMR (commonly cited surgical thresholds RVEDVi ~160 mL/m2 or RVESVi ~80 mL/m2).", "A systemic right ventricle, whether in congenitally corrected transposition or after an atrial switch (Mustard/Senning) for D-TGA, tends to fail over decades; the systemic AV valve (tricuspid) fails alongside it, and standard heart failure therapy has limited proven benefit.", "Eisenmenger patients are chronically cyanotic and secondarily erythrocytotic; routine phlebotomy is harmful, and they require pulmonary vasodilator therapy, meticulous avoidance of dehydration and afterload drops, and specialized pregnancy counseling given prohibitive maternal mortality.", "Every ACHD patient needs a durable plan for endocarditis prevention, arrhythmia surveillance, and reproductive counseling; lifelong follow-up at an ACHD-specialized center is the single highest-yield intervention."], "references": ["2018 AHA/ACC Guideline for the Management of Adults With Congenital Heart Disease (Circulation/JACC).", "2020 ESC Guidelines for the Management of Adult Congenital Heart Disease (European Heart Journal).", "2018 ESC Guidelines on the Management of Cardiovascular Diseases during Pregnancy (Regitz-Zagrosek et al.; modified WHO maternal cardiovascular risk classification).", "2021 AHA Scientific Statement on prevention of viridans group streptococcal infective endocarditis, and the 2020 ACC/AHA Valvular Heart Disease Guideline (antibiotic prophylaxis recommendations).", "BREATHE-5 randomized trial of bosentan (endothelin receptor antagonism) in Eisenmenger syndrome.", "Landmark CMR literature (e.g., Oosterhof et al., Circulation 2007; Bokma et al.) defining RV volume thresholds for pulmonary valve replacement in repaired tetralogy of Fallot."], "guidelines": [{"society": "AHA/ACC 2018", "text": "Closure of a secundum ASD is reasonable when there is evidence of right heart enlargement and net left-to-right shunting, provided pulmonary artery systolic pressure and pulmonary vascular resistance are not prohibitively elevated.", "cor": "IIa", "loe": "B"}, {"society": "AHA/ACC 2018", "text": "ASD or VSD closure should not be performed in patients with severe irreversible pulmonary arterial hypertension (Eisenmenger physiology) and no evidence of a net left-to-right shunt.", "cor": "III", "loe": "B"}, {"society": "AHA/ACC 2018", "text": "Pulmonary valve replacement is reasonable in repaired tetralogy of Fallot with severe pulmonary regurgitation and symptoms, or with progressive RV enlargement/dysfunction, to preserve long-term RV function.", "cor": "IIa", "loe": "B"}, {"society": "ESC 2020", "text": "Intervention is recommended for coarctation when the invasive peak-to-peak (or noninvasive) gradient exceeds 20 mmHg, or with a lower gradient plus significant collaterals or upper-limb hypertension and anatomic narrowing.", "cor": "I", "loe": "C"}, {"society": "AHA 2020/2021", "text": "Infective endocarditis antibiotic prophylaxis before dental procedures involving gingival manipulation is reasonable in the highest-risk anatomies: prosthetic valves or prosthetic valve-repair material, prior IE, unrepaired cyanotic CHD, CHD repaired with prosthetic material within the first 6 months, and repaired CHD with a residual defect at or adjacent to prosthetic material.", "cor": "IIa", "loe": "B"}, {"society": "ESC 2018", "text": "Pregnancy is contraindicated (modified WHO class IV) in Eisenmenger syndrome, severe pulmonary arterial hypertension, and severe systemic ventricular dysfunction (EF <30% or NYHA III-IV).", "cor": "III", "loe": "C"}], "quiz": [{"stem": "A 34-year-old with a large unrepaired VSD is referred for closure. Catheterization shows PA pressure 90/40 mmHg, PVR 9 Wood units, and a Qp:Qs of 1.0 with resting oxygen saturation of 88% that falls with exertion. What is the most appropriate management?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Surgical VSD closure to prevent further pulmonary vascular damage"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Percutaneous VSD device closure"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Medical therapy with advanced pulmonary vasodilators and no defect closure"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Serial phlebotomy to a target hematocrit below 45%"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "This is Eisenmenger physiology: severe fixed pulmonary arterial hypertension has equalized/reversed the shunt (Qp:Qs 1.0, resting cyanosis, PVR 9 WU). Closing the defect removes the pop-off and precipitates acute RV failure and death, so closure is contraindicated (Class III). The defect now acts as a protective right-to-left pressure release. Management is advanced pulmonary vasodilator therapy (endothelin receptor antagonist, with PDE5 inhibitor or prostacyclin analogue in selected patients) at an ACHD/PH center. Routine phlebotomy is harmful in these secondarily erythrocytotic patients because it worsens iron deficiency and hyperviscosity and raises stroke risk; it is reserved for symptomatic hyperviscosity with hematocrit above about 65% after excluding dehydration, with isovolumic replacement."}, {"stem": "A 28-year-old woman had complete repair of tetralogy of Fallot in infancy with a transannular patch. She is asymptomatic. CMR shows severe pulmonary regurgitation with an RV end-diastolic volume index of 165 mL/m2 and mildly reduced RV ejection fraction. What is the best next step?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Continue observation; intervene only when she becomes symptomatic"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Refer for pulmonary valve replacement"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Start an ACE inhibitor to reverse RV remodeling"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Begin sotalol for arrhythmia prophylaxis"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Chronic severe pulmonary regurgitation after a transannular patch is the dominant late lesion in repaired tetralogy. Even in an asymptomatic patient, progressive RV enlargement meeting volumetric thresholds (commonly cited RVEDVi around 160 mL/m2 or RVESVi around 80 mL/m2) together with declining RV function is an accepted trigger for pulmonary valve replacement, because RV dilation may not normalize if intervention is delayed until symptoms or severe dysfunction appear. Medical therapy does not reverse volume-overload remodeling, and prophylactic sotalol is not indicated absent documented arrhythmia."}, {"stem": "A 40-year-old man has congenitally corrected transposition (L-TGA) with no prior surgery. He presents with progressive dyspnea. Which anatomic feature best explains his heart failure?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "The left ventricle is supporting the systemic circulation and has failed"}, {"key": "B", "text": "The morphologic right ventricle supports the systemic circulation and progressively fails, along with the systemic (tricuspid) AV valve"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Severe pulmonary regurgitation has caused biventricular failure"}, {"key": "D", "text": "A residual atrial septal defect has caused right heart volume overload"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "In congenitally corrected (L-)transposition there is both atrioventricular and ventriculoarterial discordance, so blood follows a physiologically correct path but the morphologic right ventricle is connected to the aorta and serves as the systemic pump. The RV is not built for chronic systemic afterload and fails over decades, and the systemic tricuspid valve regurgitates as the RV dilates. This systemic RV failure, often with progressive AV block from the abnormal conduction axis, is the hallmark late problem. The same systemic-RV physiology occurs after atrial switch (Mustard/Senning) operations for D-TGA."}], "sections": [{"id": "learning-objectives", "title": "Learning Objectives", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Adult congenital heart disease (ACHD) now represents the majority of congenital heart disease seen in medicine, because surgical and catheter palliation of childhood lesions has produced a growing adult survivor population that outnumbers affected children. The internist and general cardiologist encounter these patients in heart failure, arrhythmia, pregnancy, and perioperative settings, and the reasoning differs substantially from acquired disease."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 1, "items": ["Frame every ACHD patient around the two questions that drive management: what is the anatomy (native, palliated, or repaired) and what is the current hemodynamic lesion.", "Apply the hemodynamic criteria for closing simple shunts (ASD, VSD, PDA) and recognize when pulmonary vascular disease makes closure dangerous.", "Define Eisenmenger physiology and manage the secondary erythrocytosis, cyanosis, and multiorgan consequences correctly.", "Identify chronic pulmonary regurgitation as the dominant late lesion of repaired tetralogy of Fallot and know the volumetric thresholds that trigger pulmonary valve replacement.", "Distinguish D-transposition (after arterial or atrial switch) from congenitally corrected L-transposition, and explain why a systemic right ventricle fails.", "Recognize coarctation, Ebstein anomaly, the Fontan circulation, and the systemic RV as distinct late-presenting entities with specific surveillance and intervention triggers.", "Deliver appropriate endocarditis prophylaxis and evidence-based pregnancy risk counseling using the modified WHO classification."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "text": "The single most important management decision in ACHD is often not a drug or a procedure. It is ensuring the patient is followed at, or co-managed with, an ACHD-certified center. Loss to follow-up during the transition from pediatric to adult care is a leading preventable cause of late morbidity."}]}, {"id": "why-it-matters", "title": "Why It Matters", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Roughly 1 in 100 live births has congenital heart disease, and with modern repair the large majority now reach adulthood. The result is a population that carries residual lesions, prosthetic material, scar-related arrhythmia substrate, and altered physiology for decades. These patients decompensate through mechanisms that are invisible if you reason only from acquired-disease templates."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "Two systematic errors recur. The first is treating a repaired lesion as cured; a repaired tetralogy or an atrial-switch transposition patient is hemodynamically stable for years and then presents with RV failure or atrial arrhythmia that was entirely predictable from the anatomy. The second is applying standard therapy blindly, such as aggressively diuresing a Fontan patient who depends on preload, phlebotomizing an Eisenmenger patient, or reflexively closing a shunt in a patient with pulmonary vascular disease. Each of these well-intentioned reflexes can be lethal."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "Never lower preload or systemic afterload abruptly in a cyanotic shunt or single-ventricle patient without understanding the shunt direction. Dropping systemic vascular resistance increases right-to-left shunting and worsens cyanosis; overdiuresis in a preload-dependent circulation causes low output."}]}, {"id": "essential-physiology", "title": "Essential Physiology: Shunts, Resistance, and Cyanosis", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Shunt physiology reduces to three variables: the size of the communication, the relative resistances of the pulmonary and systemic circulations, and the direction and magnitude of net flow. Flow follows the path of least resistance, so shunt direction is dictated by the pressure and resistance gradient, not by the anatomy of the hole itself."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "Qp:Qs", "def": "Ratio of pulmonary to systemic blood flow. 1:1 is normal. A ratio above ~1.5:1 indicates a hemodynamically significant left-to-right shunt; a ratio below 1 indicates net right-to-left shunting (cyanosis)."}, {"term": "Left-to-right shunt", "def": "Blood recirculates through the lungs, causing pulmonary overcirculation and volume loading of the receiving chambers. Acyanotic. Seen in uncomplicated ASD, VSD, PDA."}, {"term": "Right-to-left shunt", "def": "Deoxygenated blood bypasses the lungs and enters the systemic circulation, producing cyanosis. Occurs with obstruction to pulmonary flow (tetralogy) or when pulmonary vascular disease raises right-sided resistance above systemic (Eisenmenger)."}, {"term": "Pulmonary vascular resistance (PVR)", "def": "Resistance across the pulmonary bed, expressed in Wood units (mmHg per L/min). Normal is roughly 1-2 Wood units. Its magnitude and, critically, its reversibility determine whether a shunt can be safely closed."}]}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "The natural history of a chronic left-to-right shunt is the crux. Sustained pulmonary overcirculation drives pulmonary arterial remodeling: medial hypertrophy, intimal proliferation, and eventually plexiform lesions. As PVR climbs, the left-to-right shunt diminishes, then equalizes, then reverses. Once the disease is fixed and PVR approaches or exceeds systemic levels, closing the defect is fatal because the ventricle can no longer eject against the pulmonary bed and has lost its decompressing communication. The entire window for intervention lies before this transition, which is why timing is everything."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "Cyanosis in congenital disease has two mechanisms: reduced pulmonary blood flow (right-sided obstruction, as in tetralogy) or shunt reversal from pulmonary vascular disease (Eisenmenger). Distinguishing them is the first branch point at the bedside."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 3, "entries": [{"term": "Vasoreactivity / reversibility testing", "def": "At catheterization, inhaled oxygen or nitric oxide assesses whether elevated PVR falls. Operability generally favored when PVRi is roughly below 4-6 Wood units·m2 (PVR below about 2.3-5 WU) with a PVR:SVR ratio well under 0.3-0.5; a PVRi above ~8 Wood units·m2 or a near-systemic non-reactive PVR generally precludes closure. Borderline cases may use a treat-and-repair strategy."}, {"term": "Borderline PVR", "def": "Patients between clearly operable and clearly Eisenmenger. Managed at expert centers, sometimes with pulmonary vasodilators first (treat-and-repair) and repeat hemodynamics, or with fenestrated closure that leaves a controlled pop-off."}]}]}, {"id": "definitions-and-classification", "title": "Definitions and Classification", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "ACHD lesions are usefully sorted by physiology rather than by embryology. A practical bedside taxonomy separates acyanotic left-to-right shunts, cyanotic lesions, obstructive lesions, and complex single-ventricle or transposition physiologies. The 2018 AHA/ACC guideline additionally introduced an anatomic and physiologic (AP) classification that grades both lesion complexity and functional status, which predicts outcome better than anatomy alone."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "head": ["Category", "Representative lesions", "Dominant physiology"], "rows": [["Acyanotic shunt", "ASD, VSD, PDA, AV septal defect", "Left-to-right shunt, volume overload, risk of pulmonary vascular disease"], ["Cyanotic", "Tetralogy of Fallot, Eisenmenger (any shunt), tricuspid atresia", "Right-to-left shunt, hypoxemia, erythrocytosis"], ["Obstructive", "Coarctation, pulmonary/aortic stenosis, Ebstein (RV inflow)", "Pressure overload, hypertension, or AV valve dysfunction"], ["Transposition", "D-TGA (post arterial or atrial switch), L-TGA", "Discordant connections, systemic RV in atrial switch and L-TGA"], ["Single ventricle", "Fontan/Glenn palliation", "Passive pulmonary flow, preload-dependent, chronic venous congestion"]]}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "AHA/ACC anatomic class (I-III)", "def": "I = simple (isolated small ASD/VSD, mild valve disease), II = moderate complexity (repaired tetralogy, coarctation, moderate shunts), III = severe/complex (single ventricle, Fontan, cyanotic disease, transposition variants)."}, {"term": "Physiologic stage (A-D)", "def": "A = no functional limitation and normal physiology, through D = severe (refractory arrhythmia, end-organ dysfunction, severe cyanosis or pulmonary hypertension). Physiologic stage often drives management more than anatomy."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "The value of the AP classification is that two patients with identical anatomy (say, repaired tetralogy) can be class II-A or II-D depending on RV function, arrhythmia burden, and exercise capacity. Fellowship-level decisions track the physiologic stage, and re-staging at each visit is what triggers escalation."}]}, {"id": "clinical-presentation", "title": "Clinical Presentation Across the Lifespan", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Adults present in three broad patterns: the newly discovered native lesion (an adult with an undiagnosed ASD presenting with atrial fibrillation or exertional dyspnea), the repaired patient with a predictable late complication, and the palliated patient with a failing circulation. The presenting symptom is often an arrhythmia, because atrial scar and stretch make atrial tachyarrhythmias the most common reason an ACHD adult reaches a cardiologist."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 1, "items": ["Exertional dyspnea and reduced exercise tolerance, often insidious and underreported because patients have adapted their activity over years.", "Palpitations or syncope from atrial flutter/intra-atrial reentrant tachycardia, or ventricular arrhythmia in repaired tetralogy.", "Cyanosis, clubbing, and secondary erythrocytosis in Eisenmenger and unrepaired cyanotic lesions.", "Paradoxical embolism (stroke, TIA, or brain abscess) as the first clue to a right-to-left shunt.", "Heart failure signs from a failing systemic RV or single ventricle, or from chronic volume overload."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "A young adult with a cryptogenic stroke or an unexplained brain abscess should prompt a bubble study. A right-to-left shunt (PFO, ASD, or pulmonary AVM) that permits paradoxical embolism is a classic first presentation of otherwise silent congenital disease."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "Physical findings retain diagnostic power. Fixed splitting of S2 signals an ASD; a harsh holosystolic murmur at the left sternal border suggests a VSD (and paradoxically, a smaller restrictive VSD is often louder); a continuous machinery murmur under the left clavicle suggests a PDA; differential cyanosis (pink upper body, blue lower body) points to a PDA with pulmonary hypertension and reversed flow; and radio-femoral delay with upper-extremity hypertension points to coarctation."}]}, {"id": "diagnostic-approach", "title": "Diagnostic Approach", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Imaging is layered. Transthoracic echocardiography with agitated saline is the first-line study for shunt detection, chamber quantification, and estimating pulmonary pressures. When echo windows or quantification are inadequate, cardiac MRI is the reference standard for volumes, regurgitant fractions, and shunt quantification, and it has become indispensable in repaired tetralogy and systemic RV assessment. Catheterization is reserved for hemodynamics, especially PVR and reversibility, and for intervention."}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "head": ["A staged diagnostic pathway"], "items": ["Establish anatomy: TTE with agitated saline bubble study to detect and localize shunts and assess ventricular size and function.", "Quantify the lesion: CMR for RV/LV volumes, pulmonary and tricuspid regurgitant fractions, and Qp:Qs when echo is insufficient; TEE for atrial septal anatomy before device closure.", "Assess pulmonary hemodynamics: right heart catheterization for PVR, transpulmonary gradient, and vasoreactivity when shunt closure or pulmonary hypertension is in question.", "Characterize arrhythmia risk: ambulatory monitoring and, in repaired tetralogy, QRS duration and CMR-based scar/function as substrate markers.", "Stage functional capacity: cardiopulmonary exercise testing to quantify limitation objectively, which often reveals decline before symptoms are volunteered."]}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "CMR regurgitant fraction", "def": "Directly measured pulmonary regurgitant fraction (often >40% is severe) and RV volumes drive the timing of pulmonary valve replacement in repaired tetralogy, where echo systematically underestimates RV size."}, {"term": "Qp:Qs by oximetry", "def": "Calculated at catheterization from oxygen saturation step-ups. A step-up at the atrial level localizes an ASD; at the ventricular level a VSD; at the great-vessel level a PDA."}, {"term": "Vasoreactivity study", "def": "Inhaled nitric oxide or oxygen challenge during catheterization to test whether elevated PVR is reversible, distinguishing operable shunts from established Eisenmenger physiology."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "In repaired tetralogy, QRS duration on the surface ECG is a validated marker: a QRS above roughly 180 ms correlates with severe RV dilation and increased risk of sustained ventricular tachycardia and sudden death. It is one of the few cheap, reproducible risk markers in this population and should be tracked serially."}]}, {"id": "shunts-and-closure", "title": "Deep Dive: ASD, VSD, PDA and Closure Criteria", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The three classic left-to-right shunts share a management logic: close a defect that is causing hemodynamically significant recirculation and chamber remodeling, provided pulmonary vascular disease has not become fixed. What differs is the anatomy, the natural history, and the closure technique."}, {"type": "figure", "depth": 1, "src": "../assets/fig/asd-diagram.png", "alt": "Diagram of an atrial septal defect with left-to-right shunt", "caption": "Atrial septal defect: a communication in the interatrial septum lets oxygenated blood shunt left-to-right (arrows), volume-loading the right heart over time.", "credit": "Manco Capac — CC BY-SA 3.0, via Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Atrial_septal_defect-en.png"}, {"type": "figure", "depth": 1, "src": "../assets/fig/vsd-diagram.png", "alt": "Diagram of a ventricular septal defect with left-to-right shunt", "caption": "Ventricular septal defect: a defect in the interventricular septum shunts blood left-to-right (inset) — the commonest congenital cardiac lesion.", "credit": "BruceBlaus — CC BY-SA 4.0, via Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Ventricular_Septal_Defect.png"}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "head": ["Lesion", "Key subtype", "Closure indication (simplified)", "Technique"], "rows": [["ASD", "Secundum (most common, closable percutaneously); primum, sinus venosus, coronary sinus (surgical)", "RA/RV enlargement with net left-to-right shunt and non-prohibitive PVR", "Device closure for secundum with adequate rims; surgery otherwise"], ["VSD", "Perimembranous, muscular, inlet, outlet", "Significant shunt (Qp:Qs >1.5-2), LV volume overload, or recurrent endocarditis", "Surgical closure standard; selected muscular defects device-closed"], ["PDA", "Persistent ductus", "Left heart volume overload or continuous murmur with significant shunt", "Percutaneous device/coil closure in most adults"]]}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "For the secundum ASD, the decision to close rests on right heart enlargement plus evidence of net left-to-right shunting. Symptom relief, prevention of progressive RV dilation, and reduction of atrial arrhythmia burden are the goals. Adequate septal rims are required for a device; deficient rims, or sinus venosus and primum defects, mandate surgery. Importantly, primum ASD is part of the AV septal defect spectrum and carries a cleft mitral valve, and sinus venosus defects are frequently associated with anomalous pulmonary venous return, both of which change the operation."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "For VSD, most hemodynamically significant defects present and are repaired in childhood; the adult with a persistent restrictive VSD may need closure for volume overload or after an episode of endocarditis. The Eisenmenger endpoint is the boundary: a VSD with fixed severe pulmonary hypertension and shunt reversal must not be closed."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "Before closing any shunt, confirm the pulmonary vascular resistance and shunt direction. A Qp:Qs at or below 1, a resting saturation below normal, or a fixed elevated PVR are signals that the patient may have Eisenmenger physiology, in which closure is contraindicated and lethal."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 3, "entries": [{"term": "Platypnea-orthodeoxia", "def": "Positional dyspnea and desaturation (upright worse, supine better) from an intracardiac right-to-left shunt, classically an ASD/PFO. A recognized indication for closure even without large left-to-right flow."}, {"term": "Sinus venosus ASD", "def": "Defect near the SVC-RA junction, not truly in the septum, almost always accompanied by partial anomalous pulmonary venous return. Not amenable to standard device closure; requires surgical baffle."}, {"term": "Eisenmenger threshold for closure", "def": "Broadly, a PVR that is fixed and near or above systemic resistance with net right-to-left shunting contraindicates closure. Borderline cases undergo reversibility testing and expert evaluation."}]}]}, {"id": "eisenmenger", "title": "Deep Dive: Eisenmenger Syndrome", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Eisenmenger syndrome is the end stage of an untreated systemic-to-pulmonary shunt: chronic overcirculation drives irreversible pulmonary vascular disease, PVR rises to or above systemic levels, and the shunt reverses to right-to-left, producing chronic cyanosis. It is a multisystem disease, not merely a cardiac one, and its management is a study in counterintuitive rules."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "Chronic hypoxemia stimulates erythropoietin and produces secondary erythrocytosis, which is an appropriate physiologic response to improve oxygen carrying capacity, not a disease to be corrected. This is the origin of the most important management error in the field. Routine phlebotomy depletes iron, and iron-deficient microcytes are less deformable, paradoxically worsening hyperviscosity and increasing stroke risk. Phlebotomy is reserved for genuine hyperviscosity symptoms (headache, poor concentration, visual disturbance) with a hematocrit above roughly 65%, only after excluding dehydration, and with isovolumic volume replacement."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 1, "items": ["Chronic cyanosis with clubbing and secondary erythrocytosis.", "Hyperviscosity symptoms, but also a bleeding diathesis from abnormal hemostasis (a dual risk that complicates anticoagulation).", "Paradoxical embolism and cerebral abscess risk from the right-to-left shunt.", "Gout, cholelithiasis (pigment stones), and renal dysfunction as chronic sequelae.", "Progressive right heart failure and risk of sudden death."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "Do not perform routine phlebotomy in Eisenmenger patients. Do not aggressively reduce systemic vascular resistance (careful with vasodilators, epidurals, and hot environments) because falling SVR increases right-to-left shunting and deepens hypoxemia. Avoid dehydration, which raises viscosity and drops preload."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "Modern therapy has shifted from purely supportive to targeted. Advanced pulmonary vasodilators, particularly endothelin receptor antagonists (bosentan has randomized evidence in Eisenmenger from the BREATHE-5 trial), and PDE5 inhibitors and prostacyclin analogues in selected patients, improve functional capacity and hemodynamics. These patients require care at pulmonary hypertension and ACHD centers, meticulous attention to iron repletion, air-filter precautions on IV lines to prevent paradoxical air embolism, and endocarditis prophylaxis."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 3, "entries": [{"term": "Air-filter precaution", "def": "All intravenous lines in a patient with a right-to-left shunt must have air filters, because even small air bubbles can cross the shunt and cause systemic (cerebral or coronary) air embolism."}, {"term": "Iron repletion, not phlebotomy", "def": "Iron deficiency is common and harmful in erythrocytotic Eisenmenger patients. Repleting iron improves red cell deformability and symptoms; removing blood does the opposite."}, {"term": "Pregnancy in Eisenmenger", "def": "Modified WHO class IV, contraindicated. Maternal mortality has historically been reported in the 30-50% range, driven by the inability to accommodate the hemodynamic shifts of pregnancy and the peripartum period."}]}]}, {"id": "repaired-tetralogy", "title": "Deep Dive: Repaired Tetralogy of Fallot", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Tetralogy of Fallot combines a large VSD, overriding aorta, RV outflow tract obstruction, and RV hypertrophy. The unifying embryologic lesion is anterior malalignment of the outlet septum. Nearly all patients are repaired in infancy, so the adult cardiologist virtually never manages native tetralogy; the task is managing the sequelae of repair, which are dominated by what the surgeon did to relieve the outflow obstruction."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "When a transannular patch was used to open a hypoplastic pulmonary annulus, the pulmonary valve is rendered incompetent by design. The resulting chronic free pulmonary regurgitation is well tolerated for years, then insidiously dilates the right ventricle. Progressive RV dilation begets RV dysfunction, tricuspid regurgitation, exercise intolerance, atrial and ventricular arrhythmia, and eventually sudden death. The central management question is the timing of pulmonary valve replacement (PVR, here meaning valve replacement, not resistance): intervene late enough to avoid repeated valve replacements, but before RV dilation passes the point of recovery."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "head": ["Late complication", "Mechanism", "Surveillance/marker"], "rows": [["Chronic pulmonary regurgitation", "Transannular patch or valvotomy leaves incompetent valve", "CMR regurgitant fraction and serial RV volumes"], ["RV dilation/dysfunction", "Chronic volume overload", "CMR RVEDVi/RVESVi; the trigger for valve replacement"], ["Ventricular tachycardia / sudden death", "RVOT scar reentry, RV dilation", "QRS duration (>180 ms), NSVT, inducibility, LV dysfunction"], ["Atrial arrhythmia", "Atrial scar and dilation", "Ambulatory monitoring"], ["Aortic root dilation", "Intrinsic aortopathy", "Serial aortic imaging"], ["Branch pulmonary artery stenosis", "Prior shunts/surgery", "Imaging, catheter intervention"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "The commonly cited CMR thresholds for pulmonary valve replacement in the asymptomatic patient are an RV end-diastolic volume index around 160 mL/m2 or an RV end-systolic volume index around 80 mL/m2, ideally intervening before RVEDVi substantially exceeds ~160 mL/m2, above which RV volumes may not normalize after valve replacement. In symptomatic patients, or with declining RV/LV function, sustained arrhythmia, or significant TR, the threshold to intervene falls. These numbers guide, but do not replace, integrated assessment at an ACHD center."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 3, "text": "Transcatheter pulmonary valve implantation has changed the calculus for patients with a suitable RVOT conduit or bioprosthesis, allowing valve replacement without repeat sternotomy and lowering the physiologic cost of earlier intervention. Risk stratification for sudden death integrates QRS duration, nonsustained VT, inducible VT at electrophysiology study, LV as well as RV dysfunction, and extensive RVOT scar; selected high-risk patients receive an ICD, and arrhythmia can be addressed with substrate ablation at the time of surgical valve replacement."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "In repaired tetralogy, the murmur to listen for is the low-pitched diastolic decrescendo of pulmonary regurgitation, which can be soft or nearly inaudible precisely because the regurgitation is free and low-pressure. A quiet exam badly underestimates the lesion; CMR is the arbiter."}]}, {"id": "transposition", "title": "Deep Dive: Transposition of the Great Arteries", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Transposition is where careful vocabulary earns its keep, because D-TGA and L-TGA are entirely different problems that share a word. The distinction is which connections are discordant and, consequently, which ventricle ends up supporting the body."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "D-TGA (complete transposition)", "def": "Ventriculoarterial discordance only: the aorta arises from the RV and the pulmonary artery from the LV. Two parallel circulations that are incompatible with life unless a mixing communication exists. Requires surgical repair in infancy."}, {"term": "L-TGA (congenitally corrected transposition)", "def": "Both atrioventricular and ventriculoarterial discordance: blood flows in the physiologically correct direction, but the morphologic RV pumps to the aorta. 'Physiologically corrected' at the cost of a systemic RV. May go undiagnosed into adulthood."}]}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "For D-TGA, the operation defines the adult phenotype. The historical atrial switch operations (Mustard and Senning) redirect venous return at the atrial level with a baffle, leaving the morphologic RV as the systemic pump. These patients, now in adulthood, present with systemic RV failure, systemic (tricuspid) AV valve regurgitation, atrial arrhythmias from extensive atrial suture lines, baffle leaks or obstruction, and sinus node dysfunction. The modern arterial switch operation (Jatene) restores the LV as the systemic ventricle by transposing the great arteries and reimplanting the coronaries; its late issues are instead coronary ostial stenosis, neoaortic root dilation and regurgitation, and supravalvar pulmonary or branch PA stenosis."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "head": ["Repair", "Systemic ventricle", "Characteristic late complications"], "rows": [["Atrial switch (Mustard/Senning)", "Morphologic RV (systemic)", "Systemic RV failure, tricuspid regurgitation, atrial arrhythmia, baffle leak/stenosis, sinus node dysfunction"], ["Arterial switch (Jatene)", "Morphologic LV (systemic)", "Coronary ostial stenosis, neoaortic dilation/regurgitation, branch PA stenosis"], ["L-TGA (unoperated or 'corrected')", "Morphologic RV (systemic)", "Progressive systemic RV failure, tricuspid regurgitation, complete heart block"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "In L-TGA the conduction axis is anatomically abnormal and fibroses progressively, producing spontaneous complete heart block at a rate of roughly 2% per year, cumulatively affecting a large fraction of patients by mid-adulthood. Anticipate it, monitor for it, and be cautious during any procedure near the AV node. Associated lesions (VSD, pulmonary stenosis, Ebstein-like anomaly of the left-sided tricuspid valve) further shape the presentation."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 3, "text": "Managing the failing systemic RV is covered in its own section, but the key point here is anticipatory: an atrial-switch or L-TGA patient will develop systemic RV dysfunction and systemic AV valve regurgitation, and the timing of tricuspid valve intervention is contentious because operating on a valve while the RV is already failing yields poor results. Some centers pursue tricuspid repair or replacement while RV function is still preserved, precisely to protect the ventricle."}]}, {"id": "coarctation", "title": "Deep Dive: Coarctation of the Aorta", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Coarctation is a discrete narrowing of the aorta, classically juxtaductal, that behaves as a systemic obstructive lesion. It is fundamentally a disease of the whole arterial tree, not just a local stenosis, and it is strongly associated with bicuspid aortic valve (in a majority of cases) and with intracranial berry aneurysms. The adult may present with upper-extremity hypertension, headache, claudication, or an incidental murmur, and coarctation should be on the differential for any young hypertensive patient."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 1, "items": ["Upper-extremity hypertension with radio-femoral pulse delay and diminished lower-extremity pressures.", "A systolic murmur over the left interscapular area from the coarctation and collateral flow.", "Rib notching on chest radiograph from dilated intercostal collateral arteries.", "Association with bicuspid aortic valve and, importantly, intracranial aneurysms warranting consideration of screening."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "Measure blood pressure in all four extremities in any young or resistant hypertensive. An arm-to-leg systolic gradient with radio-femoral delay is the bedside signature of coarctation and is frequently missed because leg pressures are rarely checked."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "Intervention is indicated for a significant obstruction, operationally a peak-to-peak gradient across the coarctation above 20 mmHg, or a lower gradient in the presence of extensive collaterals or upper-body hypertension with anatomic narrowing. Options are surgical repair or, more commonly in adults with suitable anatomy, catheter-based stenting. The lesion is never fully cured: even after successful repair, patients have persistent or recurrent hypertension, abnormal vascular reactivity, risk of aneurysm formation at the repair site, and re-coarctation, all of which demand lifelong surveillance imaging and aggressive blood pressure control."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 3, "entries": [{"term": "Re-coarctation", "def": "Recurrent narrowing at a prior repair site, more common after infant repair. Assessed by gradient and cross-sectional imaging; often addressed by catheter stenting or balloon angioplasty."}, {"term": "Aneurysm at repair site", "def": "Late complication particularly after patch aortoplasty (Dacron patch) and balloon angioplasty. Mandates periodic CT/MR aortic imaging for life."}, {"term": "Persistent hypertension", "def": "Even with a technically perfect repair, many patients remain hypertensive due to altered arterial mechanics and baroreceptor function, a major driver of late cardiovascular events; early repair reduces but does not eliminate this."}]}]}, {"id": "ebstein", "title": "Deep Dive: Ebstein Anomaly", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Ebstein anomaly is a malformation of the tricuspid valve in which the septal and posterior leaflets are apically displaced into the RV, so that a portion of the right ventricle is 'atrialized' and functionally incorporated into the right atrium. The consequences are tricuspid regurgitation, a small and dysfunctional functional RV, right atrial enlargement, and, very commonly, an interatrial communication (PFO or ASD) that permits right-to-left shunting and cyanosis when right atrial pressure rises."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 1, "items": ["Tricuspid regurgitation with a right-sided volume-overload picture and right atrial enlargement.", "Cyanosis from right-to-left atrial shunting when a PFO/ASD is present and RA pressure is elevated.", "Arrhythmia, classically supraventricular tachycardia, with a notably high association with accessory pathways and Wolff-Parkinson-White (sometimes multiple pathways).", "A wide clinical spectrum from severe neonatal presentation to incidental diagnosis in an asymptomatic adult, depending on the degree of displacement."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "text": "The association between Ebstein anomaly and accessory pathways is strong and clinically important: right-sided accessory pathways are common, pathways may be multiple, and pre-excited atrial fibrillation is a genuine risk. Any Ebstein patient with palpitations warrants electrophysiologic evaluation, and pathway ablation is frequently performed, ideally before or at the time of any surgical valve intervention."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "Management ranges from observation in the well-compensated adult to surgical intervention for symptoms, progressive RV dilation or dysfunction, worsening cyanosis, or paradoxical embolism. The Cone reconstruction has become the preferred surgical repair, mobilizing the leaflets to create a more competent valve, with valve replacement reserved for irreparable valves. Concomitant closure of the atrial communication and surgical or catheter ablation of accessory pathways are addressed at the same time."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "On the ECG, Ebstein can show right atrial enlargement (tall P waves), right bundle branch block, and pre-excitation. The combination of cyanosis, a right-sided volume-overload murmur, and a delta wave in a young adult is a near-pathognomonic constellation."}]}, {"id": "systemic-rv", "title": "Deep Dive: The Systemic Right Ventricle", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The systemic right ventricle is one of the defining problems of adult congenital cardiology. It occurs in two settings: congenitally corrected (L-)transposition, where the morphologic RV natively supports the systemic circulation, and D-transposition after an atrial switch (Mustard or Senning), where the baffle leaves the RV as the systemic pump. In both, a ventricle designed for low-pressure pulmonary work is chronically loaded against systemic afterload, and it fails over decades."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "The morphologic RV is architecturally unsuited to systemic work: it has coarser trabeculation, a different fiber orientation optimized for volume rather than pressure, and a coronary supply and geometry that do not scale well to systemic pressure. Failure manifests as progressive systolic dysfunction, dilation, and regurgitation of the systemic AV valve, which is the tricuspid valve. Because the tricuspid valve fails as the RV dilates, systemic RV failure and systemic AV valve regurgitation advance together in a vicious cycle."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "Standard heart failure pharmacotherapy has not been shown to reliably benefit the failing systemic RV. Trials of ACE inhibitors, ARBs, and beta-blockers in this population have been largely neutral, and there is no robust evidence that guideline-directed medical therapy for the systemic LV translates to the systemic RV. Extrapolating LV heart failure regimens uncritically is a common error; management belongs at an ACHD center."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 3, "items": ["Optimize timing of systemic AV (tricuspid) valve intervention: operating before the RV ejection fraction falls too far yields better outcomes than intervening on a valve when the ventricle is already failing.", "Aggressively manage atrial arrhythmias, which are poorly tolerated and can precipitate decompensation; anticoagulation and rhythm control are often needed.", "Surveil for and treat conduction disease, particularly progressive AV block in L-TGA, with pacing where indicated (with attention to physiologic/conduction-system pacing given RV dysfunction).", "Consider cardiac resynchronization in selected patients, though evidence is far weaker than in the systemic LV.", "Refer early for advanced therapies; transplantation is the definitive option for the end-stage systemic RV, and timing referral before multiorgan dysfunction sets in is critical."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "A recurring judgment call is the failing atrial-switch patient with severe tricuspid regurgitation and a systemic RV ejection fraction already in the 30s. Valve surgery at that point often does not rescue the ventricle and may hasten decompensation, whereas earlier intervention (while RV function is preserved) protects it. The corollary is that watchful waiting until symptoms appear can forfeit the operable window, mirroring the same timing logic seen in repaired tetralogy."}]}, {"id": "guideline-directed-management", "title": "Guideline-Directed Management", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Across lesions, management coheres around a few principles: intervene on hemodynamically significant lesions before irreversible ventricular or vascular changes occur, anticipate lesion-specific arrhythmias, prevent endocarditis in the highest-risk anatomies, and counsel reproduction proactively. The details are lesion-specific but the framework is general."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "head": ["Lesion", "Primary intervention trigger", "Modality"], "rows": [["Secundum ASD", "RV enlargement + net L-to-R shunt, non-prohibitive PVR", "Device closure (adequate rims) or surgery"], ["VSD", "Significant shunt / LV overload / prior endocarditis", "Surgical (most); device for selected muscular"], ["PDA", "Left heart volume overload, significant shunt", "Percutaneous device/coil"], ["Coarctation", "Gradient >20 mmHg or hypertension + narrowing/collaterals", "Stent or surgical repair"], ["Repaired TOF", "Severe PR with symptoms or RV dilation past thresholds", "Surgical or transcatheter pulmonary valve"], ["Systemic RV / AV valve", "Severe TR before advanced RV dysfunction", "Valve surgery, HF referral, transplant"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "The recurring meta-rule of ACHD interventional timing: act before the receiving ventricle passes the point of recovery. This applies to the RV in tetralogy (RV volumes), the systemic RV in transposition (RV EF before valve surgery), and the LV in chronic left-sided volume overload. 'Wait for symptoms' frequently means 'wait too long.'"}, {"type": "p", "depth": 3, "text": "Anticoagulation in ACHD deserves special caution. Cyanotic patients have a coexisting bleeding diathesis alongside thrombotic risk, so decisions are individualized. Fontan patients have a prothrombotic tendency and often warrant thromboprophylaxis. Atrial arrhythmias in ACHD carry thromboembolic risk that conventional scores (CHA2DS2-VASc) were not derived for, and most ACHD atrial flutter/fibrillation is anticoagulated regardless of score, especially in moderate or complex anatomy."}]}, {"id": "advanced-fellow-concepts", "title": "Advanced Fellow Concepts", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "Beyond the individual lesions, several cross-cutting themes separate competent from expert management. The first is arrhythmia mechanism: most ACHD tachycardias are macroreentrant circuits around surgical scars and suture lines (intra-atrial reentrant tachycardia), not typical cavotricuspid isthmus-dependent flutter, so ablation requires detailed electroanatomic mapping and success rates are lower. Ventricular tachycardia in repaired tetralogy is macroreentry through anatomic isthmuses in the RVOT scar, amenable to substrate-based ablation, sometimes performed at the time of surgical pulmonary valve replacement."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "The second is pulmonary hypertension classification. Shunt-related PH is WHO Group 1 (pulmonary arterial hypertension associated with CHD), and its subclassification, from Eisenmenger at the severe end, through prevalent left-to-right shunt PAH, to small-defect and post-closure PAH, guides both the decision to close and the use of PAH-targeted therapy. Recognizing that a patient is beyond the operable window is a fellowship-level judgment made with catheterization hemodynamics and reversibility testing, not echo alone."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 3, "entries": [{"term": "Fontan circulation", "def": "In single-ventricle palliation, systemic venous return flows passively to the pulmonary arteries without a subpulmonary pump. Flow is preload-dependent and driven by low transpulmonary gradients; complications include Fontan-associated liver disease, protein-losing enteropathy, plastic bronchitis, atrial arrhythmia, and thrombosis. Overdiuresis and loss of sinus rhythm are poorly tolerated."}, {"term": "Treat-and-repair", "def": "For borderline-operable shunts with elevated but partially reversible PVR, a strategy of PAH-targeted therapy first, then reassessment of hemodynamics, sometimes enabling later safe closure."}, {"term": "Intra-atrial reentrant tachycardia (IART)", "def": "Scar-mediated macroreentrant atrial tachycardia, the dominant arrhythmia in repaired ACHD. Often slow (may conduct 1:1 with hemodynamic collapse), poorly rate-controlled, and best treated with mapping-guided ablation and anticoagulation."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "A slow atrial flutter around 150 bpm in a repaired ACHD patient can conduct 1:1 to the ventricle, especially on antiarrhythmics that slow the atrial rate, producing rapid 1:1 AV conduction with hemodynamic collapse. This is why class IC and III agents in ACHD flutter are often paired with AV nodal blockade, and why ablation is favored over lifelong pharmacologic suppression."}]}, {"id": "pregnancy-and-endocarditis", "title": "Pregnancy and Endocarditis Considerations", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Two counseling domains touch nearly every ACHD patient: reproductive risk and endocarditis prevention. Both are frequently mishandled by non-specialists, either through unwarranted alarm or dangerous complacency."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Pregnancy imposes a 40-50% rise in blood volume and cardiac output, a fall in systemic vascular resistance, and a hypercoagulable state, with further abrupt shifts at delivery. Whether a heart tolerates this is captured by the modified WHO maternal cardiovascular risk classification, which stratifies from class I (no detectable increased risk) to class IV (pregnancy contraindicated)."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "head": ["mWHO class", "Representative ACHD conditions", "Implication"], "rows": [["I (low risk)", "Small/repaired simple lesions, mild pulmonary stenosis, repaired ASD/VSD/PDA without sequelae", "Routine obstetric care acceptable"], ["II-III (intermediate)", "Repaired tetralogy, most unrepaired shunts without PH, mild systemic ventricular dysfunction", "Care at expert center, increased surveillance"], ["III (high risk)", "Systemic RV, Fontan, cyanotic disease, mechanical valve", "Intensive multidisciplinary management; counsel on substantial risk"], ["IV (contraindicated)", "Eisenmenger, severe PAH, severe systemic ventricular dysfunction (EF <30% / NYHA III-IV), severe symptomatic obstruction", "Pregnancy contraindicated; discuss termination and reliable contraception"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "Eisenmenger syndrome and severe pulmonary arterial hypertension are mWHO class IV: pregnancy is contraindicated because maternal mortality is prohibitively high. The peripartum and immediate postpartum periods, when volume shifts and afterload changes are greatest, carry the highest risk. Reliable contraception counseling is a core part of care, with attention to the thrombotic risk of estrogen-containing methods in cyanotic and Fontan patients."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "For endocarditis, modern guidance has narrowed prophylaxis to the highest-risk anatomies. Antibiotic prophylaxis before dental procedures involving manipulation of gingival tissue or the periapical region is reasonable in: prosthetic heart valves or prosthetic material used for valve repair, previous infective endocarditis, unrepaired cyanotic CHD (including palliative shunts and conduits), CHD repaired with prosthetic material during the first 6 months after the procedure, and repaired CHD with residual defects at or adjacent to the site of a prosthetic patch or device (which inhibit endothelialization). Beyond antibiotics, meticulous oral and skin hygiene is emphasized for all ACHD patients, and prophylaxis is not recommended for most repaired simple lesions without residual defects."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 3, "entries": [{"term": "Highest-risk anatomies (prophylaxis reasonable)", "def": "Prosthetic valves/material, prior IE, unrepaired cyanotic CHD, repaired CHD with prosthetic material in the first 6 months, and repaired CHD with residual defect adjacent to prosthetic material."}, {"term": "Not recommended", "def": "Routine prophylaxis for isolated secundum ASD, fully repaired VSD/PDA/ASD beyond 6 months without residual defect, and for non-dental, non-high-risk procedures."}, {"term": "Estrogen and thrombosis", "def": "Combined hormonal contraception raises thrombotic risk; in cyanotic, Fontan, and other prothrombotic ACHD physiologies, progestin-only or intrauterine methods are generally preferred."}]}]}, {"id": "bedside-pearls", "title": "Bedside Pearls", "body": [{"type": "list", "depth": 1, "items": ["Fixed splitting of S2 = ASD until proven otherwise; a smaller restrictive VSD is often louder than a large one because higher velocity generates more turbulence.", "Differential cyanosis (pink hands, blue feet) points to a PDA with pulmonary hypertension and reversed ductal flow.", "Four-extremity blood pressures on every young hypertensive; radio-femoral delay is the coarctation you would otherwise miss.", "A young cryptogenic stroke or a brain abscess demands a bubble study to find a right-to-left shunt.", "In repaired tetralogy the pulmonary regurgitation murmur is soft precisely because it is severe and low-pressure; trust the CMR, not the stethoscope."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "When an ACHD patient decompensates, first ask 'what is the anatomy and what is the current lesion,' then ask 'have they lost sinus rhythm.' New atrial arrhythmia is among the most common precipitants of decompensation across ACHD, from the Fontan to the systemic RV to the repaired tetralogy, and restoring rhythm is often more valuable than escalating diuresis."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 3, "items": ["Never phlebotomize the stable erythrocytotic Eisenmenger patient; replete iron instead.", "Put air filters on every IV line in any patient with a right-to-left shunt.", "Do not aggressively drop SVR in a right-to-left shunt; it deepens cyanosis.", "In L-TGA, anticipate spontaneous complete heart block (~2% per year) and protect the AV node during procedures.", "Anticoagulate most ACHD atrial arrhythmia regardless of CHA2DS2-VASc, which was not validated in this population."]}]}, {"id": "common-mistakes", "title": "Common Mistakes", "body": [{"type": "list", "depth": 1, "items": ["Treating a repaired lesion as cured and discharging the patient from cardiology follow-up; repaired tetralogy, atrial-switch transposition, and coarctation all have predictable late complications requiring lifelong surveillance.", "Closing a shunt without confirming pulmonary vascular resistance and shunt direction, risking a catastrophic outcome in unrecognized Eisenmenger physiology.", "Routine phlebotomy in Eisenmenger patients, which worsens iron deficiency, hyperviscosity, and stroke risk.", "Waiting for symptoms before intervening on pulmonary regurgitation in repaired tetralogy, allowing RV dilation to pass the point of recovery.", "Extrapolating systemic-LV heart failure drug regimens to the failing systemic RV, where they lack proven benefit."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "Aggressive diuresis in a Fontan or other preload-dependent circulation causes low output, not decongestion, because forward flow through the lungs is passive and preload-dependent. Congestion in a Fontan often reflects circuit obstruction, arrhythmia, or ventricular dysfunction that needs a mechanistic diagnosis, not reflexive escalation of loop diuretics."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 3, "items": ["Applying CHA2DS2-VASc to decide against anticoagulation in complex ACHD atrial arrhythmia, where thromboembolic risk is underestimated by the score.", "Missing the Ebstein-accessory pathway association and failing to evaluate palpitations, leaving a substrate for pre-excited atrial fibrillation.", "Using estrogen-containing contraception in cyanotic or Fontan patients without accounting for thrombotic risk.", "Operating on a systemic AV (tricuspid) valve only after the systemic RV has already failed, forfeiting the window when valve surgery could have protected the ventricle.", "Overlooking neoaortic root dilation and coronary ostial stenosis in the arterial-switch patient because attention defaults to the systemic LV."]}]}, {"id": "references", "title": "References", "body": [{"type": "list", "depth": 1, "items": ["2018 AHA/ACC Guideline for the Management of Adults With Congenital Heart Disease.", "2020 ESC Guidelines for the Management of Adult Congenital Heart Disease.", "2018 ESC Guidelines on the Management of Cardiovascular Diseases during Pregnancy (modified WHO maternal cardiovascular risk classification).", "2021 AHA scientific statement on prevention of infective endocarditis and the 2020 ACC/AHA valvular heart disease guideline (antibiotic prophylaxis).", "Landmark cardiac MRI literature defining RV volume thresholds for pulmonary valve replacement in repaired tetralogy of Fallot (e.g., Oosterhof et al., Circulation 2007).", "BREATHE-5 randomized trial of endothelin receptor antagonism (bosentan) in Eisenmenger syndrome."]}]}]};
